      "h": "Why Terminology Matters in Texas History",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> The term 'Texican' refers to early inhabitants of Texas with Mexican cultural ties. It is often confused with 'Texian' and 'Texan', which evolved later with shifting political identities. Clarifying these terms helps prevent misconceptions about Texas history.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from lauriemooremoore.com; everything-everywhere.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Explore the meaning of 'Texican' and its historical roots</li><li>Distinguish 'Texican' from 'Texian' and 'Texan'</li><li>Set the stage for deeper historical context</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Consider a settler in early 19th-century Texas of Mexican descent—this person would be a 'Texican', distinct from Anglo settlers called 'Texians'.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Reflect on what you think 'Texican' means and how it differs from 'Texian' or 'Texan'.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming 'Texican' and 'Texan' are interchangeable without historical nuance.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> lauriemooremoore.com; everything-everywhere.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup></p>"
