    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">03</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Terminology Evolution</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">From Texican to Texian to Texan: A Timeline</h2><ul><li>'Texican': Mexican residents pre-1836</li><li>'Texian': Anglo settlers and revolutionaries during Texas Revolution</li><li>'Texan': Post-independence citizens of the Republic and State of Texas</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">The terms evolved alongside political changes: 'Texican' during Mexican rule, 'Texian' during the revolution, and 'Texan' after independence, reflecting shifting identities. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> During the Texas Revolution (1835-1836), Anglo settlers called themselves 'Texians' to assert a new political identity distinct from 'Texicans'.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Match each term to its corresponding historical period and political context.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Ignoring the political significance behind these terms and treating them as synonyms.</p></div></div>",
