    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">12</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Summary</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Key Takeaways: Defining the Texicans and Their World</h2><ul><li>'Texican' denotes Mexican residents of Texas before independence</li><li>Terminology evolved with political changes: Texican → Texian → Texan</li><li>Mexican colonization policies shaped settlement and society</li><li>Texican identity was culturally diverse and politically complex</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Understanding who the Texicans were requires grasping terminology, political context, and cultural hybridity, setting a foundation for further study. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Recognizing a Texican as distinct from a Texian helps clarify historical narratives about Texas independence.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Summarize how terminology and political context influence historical identity.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Overlooking the interplay of culture and politics in defining Texicans.</p></div></div>",
