    "eyebrow": "Settlement Patterns",
    "num": "13",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">13</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Settlement Patterns</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Texican Colonies: Locations and Land Use</h2><ul><li>Texicans established colonies primarily along rivers and fertile lands</li><li>Land grants from Mexican authorities shaped settlement locations</li><li>Agriculture and ranching were main land uses supporting frontier life</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican settlements were strategically located near water sources and arable land, influenced by Mexican colonization policies granting land to settlers. These colonies formed the backbone of Texican society, focusing on farming and cattle ranching to sustain their communities and economy. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> The colony of Gonzales was established near the Guadalupe River, utilizing fertile soil for crops and nearby grazing land for cattle.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify on a map where Texican colonies were established and explain why those locations were chosen.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming Texican settlements were randomly placed without regard to geography or Mexican land grant policies.</p></div></div>",
