    "eyebrow": "Frontier Lifestyle",
    "num": "14",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">14</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Frontier Lifestyle</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Daily Life and Economy in Texican Settlements</h2><ul><li>Texicans lived a frontier lifestyle blending farming, ranching, and trade</li><li>Communities were often isolated, requiring self-sufficiency</li><li>Trade with Native Americans and neighboring settlements was common</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Life in Texican colonies was shaped by the demands of frontier living. Settlers combined agriculture and cattle ranching to sustain themselves, while isolation fostered a culture of self-reliance. Trade networks developed with Native American tribes and other settlers to exchange goods and services. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Texican families grew staple crops like corn and raised cattle, while trading hides and livestock with nearby tribes for tools and food.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Describe how the frontier lifestyle influenced Texican economic activities and social interactions.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Overlooking the importance of trade and interaction with Native Americans in Texican daily life.</p></div></div>",
