    "eyebrow": "Primary Sources",
    "num": "27",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">27</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Primary Sources</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Texican Military Records: Defense and Conflict</h2><ul><li>Military documents record Texican involvement in conflicts</li><li>They reveal alliances and tensions with Mexican and indigenous forces</li><li>These records illustrate Texican agency in regional security</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Military records from the Texican period provide evidence of their participation in defense efforts and conflicts, highlighting their complex role between Mexican authorities and indigenous groups. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s14\">[14]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s15\">[15]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A muster roll listing Texican militia members shows community defense organization and political affiliations.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Examine a military record excerpt to identify Texican motivations and alliances.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Avoid interpreting military involvement as solely loyalist or rebellious; motivations were often mixed.</p></div></div>",
