    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">31</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Terminology Evolution</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">The Emergence of ‘Texan’: Post-Independence Identity</h2><ul><li>‘Texan’ became the dominant term after Texas independence</li><li>Represents a unified state identity transcending earlier divisions</li><li>Reflects political sovereignty and cultural integration</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Following independence, ‘Texan’ emerged as the preferred term, symbolizing a new political entity and collective identity distinct from Mexican or colonial origins. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Official documents from the Republic of Texas era use ‘Texan’ to denote citizenship and statehood.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Compare uses of ‘Texan’ and ‘Texian’ in historical texts and infer identity shifts.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Avoid retroactively applying ‘Texan’ to periods before independence.</p></div></div>",
