      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texican cultural practices are difficult to reconstruct fully due to scarce written documentation and the underuse of oral histories, which are crucial for capturing lived experiences and cultural blending (s2, s10).</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; libguides.fau.edu. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Limited written records on daily life and traditions</li><li>Oral histories are underrepresented in archives</li><li>Cultural hybridity complicates clear categorization</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>For instance, many Texican festivals and rituals were passed down orally and rarely recorded in official documents.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Reflect on how reliance on written sources might bias our view of Texican culture.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Overlooking oral traditions and focusing solely on official records.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; libguides.fau.edu <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup></p>"
