    "id": "slide51",
    "eyebrow": "Indigenous Interactions",
    "num": "39",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">39</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Indigenous Interactions</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Contested Points in Texican and Indigenous Relations</h2><ul><li>Sources often reflect colonial biases against Native peoples</li><li>Complex alliances and conflicts are underdocumented</li><li>Indigenous perspectives are largely absent in Texican narratives</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Historical accounts of Texican interactions with indigenous groups are frequently biased, emphasizing conflict and marginalizing Native perspectives, which limits a balanced understanding of these relationships (s7, s10). <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Many Texican documents portray Native tribes as hostile, but archaeological and oral evidence suggest nuanced alliances and trade relations.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Analyze how source bias might affect interpretations of Texican-indigenous relations.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Accepting colonial narratives at face value without seeking indigenous viewpoints.</p></div></div>",
