      "h": "Navigating Source Bias in Indigenous Relations",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Historical accounts of Texican interactions with indigenous groups are frequently biased, emphasizing conflict and marginalizing Native perspectives, which limits a balanced understanding of these relationships (s7, s10).</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from lauriemooremoore.com; libguides.fau.edu. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Sources often reflect colonial biases against Native peoples</li><li>Complex alliances and conflicts are underdocumented</li><li>Indigenous perspectives are largely absent in Texican narratives</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Many Texican documents portray Native tribes as hostile, but archaeological and oral evidence suggest nuanced alliances and trade relations.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Analyze how source bias might affect interpretations of Texican-indigenous relations.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Accepting colonial narratives at face value without seeking indigenous viewpoints.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> lauriemooremoore.com; libguides.fau.edu <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup></p>"
