    "eyebrow": "Source Bias",
    "num": "40",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">40</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Source Bias</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Recognizing Biases in Texican Historical Sources</h2><ul><li>Official documents reflect political agendas</li><li>Personal letters may reveal subjective viewpoints</li><li>Later historical interpretations can impose present-day values</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican historical sources vary in perspective and purpose, often containing biases that reflect the authors' political, social, or personal positions, which must be critically evaluated (s2, s7, s10). <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Land grant records may emphasize settler claims while ignoring indigenous land use.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify potential biases in a given Texican primary source excerpt.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Treating all historical documents as equally objective and factual.</p></div></div>",
