    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">43</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Review</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Settlement Patterns and Lifestyle of the Texicans</h2><ul><li>Texicans established colonies primarily along rivers and fertile lands</li><li>They practiced agriculture, ranching, and trade with indigenous groups</li><li>Frontier life involved adaptation to diverse environments and social networks</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican settlement was strategic and adaptive, reflecting both environmental opportunities and cultural interactions (s2, s7). <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> The establishment of communities near the Brazos and Colorado Rivers facilitated farming and trade.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Describe how geography influenced Texican settlement choices.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Ignoring the role of indigenous trade networks in Texican economy.</p></div></div>",
